                <head>215. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In a meeting with Department of State officers and National Security Council
                    staff members on June 21, 1974, Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                        >Kissinger</persName> discussed ongoing negotiations with the Soviets in the
                    context of the upcoming summit meeting between President <persName
                        corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> and Soviet General Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_BLI1">Brezhnev</persName>. A memorandum of the conversation of
                    the meeting reads in part: <list>
                        <item>“<persName corresp="#p_SHH1">Sonnenfeldt</persName>: In <gloss
                                target="#t_CSCE1">CSCE</gloss>, we will just have to wait until
                            Moscow, where we can be sure that <persName corresp="#p_BLI1"
                                >Brezhnev</persName> will unload on the President.</item>
                        <item>“Secretary: They say the present text [of the draft <gloss
                                target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss>-Soviet communiqué] is less than last
                            year. And you know that <gloss target="#t_CSCE1">CSCE</gloss> is going
                            to end in a summit.</item>
                        <item>“<persName corresp="#p_SHH1">Sonnenfeldt</persName>: But we are saying
                            more this year. We are really giving them more than in the past.</item>
                        <item>“Secretary: Then let’s stick for awhile. I wonder what makes them
                            think that in the communiqué they can make us change our
                            well-thought-out positions.”</item>
                        <item>Later, discussion turned to <gloss target="#t_MBFR1"
                            >MBFR</gloss>:</item>
                        <item>“<persName corresp="#p_SHH1">Sonnenfeldt</persName>: What about <gloss
                                target="#t_MBFR1">MBFR</gloss>?</item>
                        <item>“Secretary: <persName corresp="#p_DAF1">Dobrynin</persName> said they
                            would continue to stick with their present position.</item>
                        <item>“<persName corresp="#p_SHH1">Sonnenfeldt</persName>: And we should
                            stick to ours. Did you give him any indication we would
                            compromise?</item>
                        <item>“Secretary: No. The President wants it, but any deal in Moscow would
                            get us into a terrible mess with the Allies.” (National Archives, <gloss
                                target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Records of the Office of the
                            Counselor, Entry 5339, Box 8, Soviet-Summit, 1974)</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
